column168: Trailer 550031 moved from Dayton, OH to Lafayette, IN (LFT/260) on 12/03/12. Upon arriving at the LFT/260 terminal at 08:40 am, trailer was spotted in the yard. At 9:15 am, Driver - Don Carnes opened doors of trailer to spot in dock. Upon opening the trailer doors, Don smelled a strong odor of paint and noticed that a drum had been punctured at the top and had spilled a very small amount of liquid (approximately 4 Ounces). Don informed me of the situation (TM-Shane Strasser). After taking pictures of the spill, we immediately pulled the punctured drum off the back of the trailer, while still in the yard, and placed it into a containment drum. The 4 ounces of liquid remaining in the trailer was wiped up with a rag. The rag was placed inside the containment drum prior to closure. The spill was contained within the confines of the trailer.
column169: Drum was punctured by Forklift. Additional forklift training at offending terminal should be conducted.

column168: R&L Carriers contacted ERTS to dispatch a contractor to cleanup a UN1824 Sodium Hydroxide release in a trailer at the R&L Terminal in Fresno, CA. It was reported that 18 of the 22 five gallon buckets were damaged and released ~ 2 gallons of material to the trailer floor. The contractor consolidate the damaged containers into 55 gallon drums and transported them for disposal. They then neutralized the released material, applied absorbents to the impacted areas and worked the absorbents in. They then swept the impacted areas clean and all waste was containerized for pending disposal.

column168: Our tractor trailer tanker was delivering regular gasoline into an underground storage tank at a retail gasoline station. Near the end of the delivery the underground tank reached it's capacity and gasoline backed up into the vent system. About 3-4 gallons came out the vent before the driver closed the delivery valve. The product was contained on the concrete and pavment, with about 2 gallons collected into a pail with a hand pump and returned to inventory. No product left the covered surface. Overfill device on the station underground tank did not activate and repairs will be made.
column169: We will be working with the station owner to make sure overfill protection device (flapper valve/check valve) is repalced and functioning. Calibration of the station inventory monitoring system will also be checked against actual tank stick readings to ensure accuracy at time of ordering and delivery.

column168: Sequence of events that led to the incident:    On 12/3/12, Tank Trailer 68901 was loaded with 50% Caustic Soda at approximately 5:00 p.m.  The Terre Haute personnel have an established practice to apply steam to the tanker when it will set overnight during cold weather to prevent the potential for freezing.  To minimize any potential problems with pressure build up, the dome lid is cracked open by resting one of the bolts between the dome lid and the opening of the dome or man way.    On 12/4/12, The Terre Haute Driver, Chuck McDowell, coupled to the tanker.  He disconnected the steam line: however, he failed to close and tighten the bolts on the dome lid.    Chuck left the Terre Haute Plant on Lockport Road at approximately 5:40 a.m.  He weighed the tanker on the scales across the street.  He then proceeded Northbound on 14th Street (Lockport Road) and turned left (West) on Voorhees Street.  When the driver stopped at the traffic light at 7th and Voorhees, the liquid apparently splashed out of the man way and onto the street; however, the driver was not aware of any problem at this time.  At approximately 5:45 a.m., the Terre Haute driver stopped again between 4th and 3rd Street in a parking lot (Show Me’s Restaurant) in order to walk to Thortons Convenient Store.  It was at this time one of our other drivers stopped at the parking lot and detected the material was dripping from the overflow in the parking lot, too.  They verified that the dome lid was cracked open, and Chuck immediately closed and tightened the dome lid.    Actions taken at the time it was discovered:    The other driver assisted with our defensive action by driving back to our plant to get some floor dry (absorbent) and report the problem to their supervisor.  The supervisor instructed several other drivers to help assist with the confinement and containment of the material and help with the traffic control.  As a result, the Brenntag personnel absorbed the material at both the 7th Street location and the material in the parking lot.  The material was properly disposed as a non-hazardous solid waste.    The Brenntag Operations Manager and Operations Supervisor was notified and arrived on the scene at approximately 6:35 a.m. to assist with the traffic control.    At approximately 6:44 a.m., Police Officer Minnick (#232) arrived on the scene.  At 6:45 a.m., the Fire Department Personnel were dispatched to assist with the clean-up activities, too.  The Hazmat Team confirmed the residue would not be harmful to the environment and a decision was made to wash down any traces of the material with their fire hoses.    The Firefighters cleared the scene by 9:00 a.m.      Package Failure:    There was no damage to the package (Tanker 68001).  The only failure related to not properly securing the dome lid.    Estimated Duration of Release:    The estimated duration of the release from 7th Street to the 4th Street Parking was approximately less than two (2) minutes.    The estimated dura
column169: As part of our General Policy and Procedure for any Out of Service (OOS) Violations that are considered preventable, we followed our procedure GP&P 19930180 for the appropriate disciplinary action for the employee that was directly responsible for the inspection and securement.    The incident was also used as a moment of high influence in our safety meetings at the Terre Haute Facility as a refresher on the proper operating procedure for inspection of the tanker which includes securing the dome lid before coupling to the tanker if the tanker is being steam heated.    We are in-process of implementing a documented procedure to support the established practice for tanker loading and delivery so it will include a Checklist as a record to show conformance to the procedure for proper inspection and securement prior to leaving the facility.  This especially holds true for the verification that the dome lid has been secured when the tanker has been steam heated overnight.

column169: THIS TYPE OF SITUATION IS VERY DIFFICULE TO PREVENT SINCE THE LEAKING DRUM GAVE NO IMPRESSION THAT IT WOULD LEAK WHEN IT WAS INITIALLY PICKED UP FROM THE WASTE GENERATOR. ALL WE CAN DO IS TO CONTINUE TO CLOSELY INSPECT LOADS FOR ANY SIGN OF A POTENTIAL RUPTURE AND REJECT LOADS THAT LOOK LIKE THEY CAN PRESENT A PROBLEM.

column168: Michael Middleton with the DHL Express DCA Service Center contacted our Hotline to report a leaking Dangerous Goods in Excepted Quantities shipment in their warehouse. Prior to his call, the shipment had been placed into a large plastic bin to contain the leak and the plastic bin had been moved to the haz area.  PSC Environmental was contacted and spill responders were dispatched to DCA Service Center.  Upon their arrival, the shipment was discovered to contain 8 x 1 liter glass bottles of UN1170, PG II.  Due to the lack of cushioning material in the shipment, 1 glass bottle broke, leaking its entire contents. The area was cleaned and the shipment was bagged and placed into a salvage drum.  The shipment was marked and labeled as Dangerous Goods in Excepted Quantities.  The contents exceed what is allowed to ship as Dangerous Goods in Excepted Quantities.

The local fire department secured the leak and released material with absorbents. The contractor arrived on site and over packed the damaged container. They then neutralized the released material, applied additional absorbents, worked them in and swept the impacted trailer floor and pavement clean. All waste was containerized and transported off site for pending disposal.

column168: On Monday, December 10, 2012, at 1130 hours CST, Mr. Ken Dechant from Werner Enterprises contacted ACT Environmental & Infrastructure, Inc. (A•C•T) Project Manager, Gary Weiss to request assistance with an possible release of ethylene oxide indie a Werner Enterprise trailer (trailer #41703).  The release occurred at 2705 Burris Road in Davie, Florida.  Mr. Dechant advised that while off-loading a trailer that contained ethylene oxide, a colorless gas at room temperature, a worker reportedly became ill.  Another worker during the wash-out of the trailer also reportedly became ill.  A•C•T was requested to respond to analyze the air inside the trailer for residual ethylene oxide.     Upon arrival at the site, our response team met with the driver and was advised the current situation.  After a conducting a brief safety meeting and review of the MSDS our responder donned the proper PPE (Level C) and prepared to enter the trailer.  Utilizing an Ultra Ray PID our responder first checked a sample of the ambient air away from the suspect trailer. This sample showed a level of .75 ppm.  Upon entering the trailer, air samples were tested at sevent (7) locations throughout trailer.  All test samples were at or below the outside ambient air.

column168: On December 6, 2012, at 2113 hours, a car inspector at the CSXT Queensgate Terminal, Cincinnati, Ohio noticed a vapor cloud being emitted from PROX 14978, a residue tank car of UN1789, Hydrochloric Acid. The tank car was isolated. The shipper, AK Steel, was notified via Chemtrec, report # 2012-12-06-00198. A CSXT hazardous material manager, and Summit Environmental Services, a CSXT emergency response contractor, were dispatched to the scene.  Inspection of the tank car revealed that four (4) of four (4) blind flange bolts and four (4) of four (4) bolts on the lower three inch flange both on the liquid line were in a less than tool tight condition. There was a residual amount of hydrochloric acid on the liquid line assembly and beneath it on the pressure plate. The bolts were tightened appropriately and the residual acid was wiped from the tank car. The shipper representative, Larry Sutthoff, was notified of the situation found. The release was secured and PROX 14978 was released for disposition.  This incident did require a special move.    NARRI: 5x(4+5+0)x(2+0) = 90  Cause code:115

A valve at the end of a discharge hose that was connected to a transport trailer was opened slightly by an unknown source. The site was not manned at the time and approximatelt 1,200 gallons of 20% biodiesel and 80% #2 fuel oil spilled onto the asphalt and concrete lot. The fuel did not leave the site and was contained on asphalt and concrete. A small portion of the product did enter an existing groundwater extraction well that remained at the site from a previous environmental clean up. The product contained on the asphalt was collected and disposed of utilizing a vacuum truck. The vacuum truck also pumped approximately 1,000-gallons of petroleum contaminated groundwater from the extraction well which was hauled off site for disposal. The remaining fuel residue on the concrete and asphalt was absorbed utilizing oil dry and the waste was collected into nine 55-gallon drums for disposal.

column168: Operator was loading a Hydrochloric Acid Truck per current Operating Procedure.  The loading pump computer was set to maximum capacity of the trailer.  The Trailer overflowed after the pump kicked off; speculate the residual in the loading lines spilled out of trailer.  Approximately 5-10 gallons spilled down side of the trailer to the pavement below.  Hy-dry was applied to the spill and cleaned.  The dome and trailer were washed down of any residual product.  Another 50 gallons was pumped out of the truck to ensure no further overflow.
column169: The Operating Procedures were reviewed and revised to allow for 1% less fill than maximum capacity of the trailer.  Training to new operating procedure to take place after revision.  The flow meters for loading Hydrochloric Acid will be added to a regular preventative maintenance schedule to ensure accuracy.

column168: A hazmat release of approximately two ounces of liquid asphalt (elevated temperature liquid) occurred during a transfer of asphalt from tank truck to rail car at the Birmingham TRANSFLO terminal. While the transloading employee was attempting to clear the asphalt transfer product line with air after completing the first half of a split load, the 1-1/2 inch gasket on the air line ball valve failed. This failure of the gasket allowed approximately 2 ounces of liquid asphalt tar (elevated temperature liquid)  to release onto the pavement of the transfer area. No injuries. No drains were impacted. No off-site consequences.
column169: Root Causes: Equipment Failure- The 1 ½ inch gasket on the air line ball valve failed while the product line was being cleared.     Corrective Action: The released asphalt was cleaned up and the 1 ½ inch gasket was replaced with a new gasket.

column168: At approximately 11:45 AM on 12.21.2012 KCS a KCS employee reportedan odor emitting from NATX 60028 or ACFX 94870 in the Beaumont yard in Beaumont, TX. The cars were set out and isolated for response at the south end of Beaumont yard. Both cars were loads Methyl Mercaptan out of Arkema Beaumont.There are no exposures or injuries reported from this odor. Emergency notifications were made and KCS mobilized safety qualified response contractor.    Upon arrival, the response contractor verified securement of railcars and accessed to performed leak detection investigation. Upon further inspection, tank car ACFX 94870 was verified cleared of any leaks. After more leak detection was performed, it was determined that there was a very small leak originating from the Liquid Valve (B end) valve stem packing. The packing was tightened  turn to stop the release. The repair was verified by snoop-check and by air monitoring meter. Both cars were verified secure and released back into transportation.    File Note Item 19-the quantity released was A MINOR VAPOR RELEASE and therefore the amount cannot be quantified. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities,   and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence.     It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. To improve communications the shipper can provide contact information in this web site (Contact Network) to better facilitate incident response and post incident communications as applicable.

During routine inspections of the yard, Chip Heard, MHM for Union Pacific found UTLX 211181 with product on the side of the car.  Upon inspection of the car, it was determined that the leak was originating from the manway due to the swing bolts not being properly secured.  One swing bolt was in the down position and 5 of the remainig 7 bolts were less than tool tight.  The seal was removed and the manway gasket was checked and in good condition.  The manway was closed, properly secured and sealed.  A contractor was called to wipe down the exterior of the car.  Approximately 10 gallons of product released from the car.
column169: Talked with both shipper and loader on proper securement techniques.

column168: The tank car GATX 74013 was being switched at the Lake Charles train yard, and a yard employee claimed he was splashed by product coming from the top of the car.  The car was isolated on track 509 and representatives from the shipper PPG industries and Hazardous Materials Manager Tom Robinson responded to investigate the tank car.  Upon investigation the frangible rupture disc on the safety relief vent burst and was the cause of the release.  A replacement rupture disc was placed in the safety relief vent and the car was secured for movement.  No further remediation was required.

column168: Energy Dispatch vehicle was traveling NB on I-69 in Humble, TX when, for reasons unknown at this point, the truck and trailer rolled over onto the driver side, slid down the exit ramp and caught fire. column168: On December 18, 2012 at approximately 7:40 AM, a Quality Carrier Bulk Transportation truck had started loading Methanol when the IMTT Operator  discovered Methanol dripping from the inlet loading line of the trailer. The IMTT Operator immediately placed a 5-gallon pail under the trailer to collect the dripping Methanol and notified his supervisor. The Quality Carrier Truck was secured and moved to an area with secondary containment and then contents  transferred to another truck which was dispatched to the area. The transfer was completed without incident and the Quality Carrier Bulk truck was released from  the IMTT Terminal.
column169: IMTT-Bayonne contacted the customer of the product to inform them of the incident. The customer subsequently contacted the transportation company and will address any mechanical or structural issues with the truck or related components.

column168: A vehicle operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Svc at Clean Harbor’s in transit facility in Menomonee Falls,WI for the purpose of consolidating less than  truck load quantities of hazardous waste for continuing transportation to the intended waste management facility. While transferring one container, the driver noticed material leaking from a puncture hole near the bottom of the drum.Facility personnel placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum along with all clean-up debris from the van trailer. The container was secured and was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: At the time the driver accepted the container for transportation, no evidence of leaking was observed.  It is suspected that the drum hit the corner of a pallet causing the puncture. In order to prevent a recurrence, the driver in posession of the shipment was spoken to and instructed to ensure that each drum is inspected before it is accepted for transportation. Any container that is found to have suspect structural integrity is to be either transferred into a suitable container or placed into a salvage drum for continued transportation.

column168: At 1245 hrs an odor of sulfur was reported from tank car UTLX 60777 in Track RT15.  Employees were removed from area and sheltered in place.  NS Environmental personnel and a contractor responded and found over 200ppm H2S around the manway nozzle.  Manway bolts were tight.  Manway cover was opened which revealed a deteriorated gasket which allowed vapors to escape.  The manway cover and nozzle were cleaned with a wire brush, a new manway gasket was applied, bolts tightened and manway metered again.  Zero ppm was found around the manway after gasket replacement and proper securement.
column169: Shipper should do a better job checking gaskets prior to loading.  Suggest replacing gasket every trip.

column168: Carman working outbound train T58 noticed liquid dripping from the top of tank car car ETCX 230521.  The car was isolated and NS Environmental and a contractor responded. Car will be moved on OTMA to Knigsport, TN for cleaning and repair.

column42: AMINE, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, FLAMMABLE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, LIQUID, CORROSIVE, FLAMMABLE, N.O.S.
column168: Driver was using a pump to unload product from cargo tank to the customer storage tank.  As soon as he started product flowing, it sprayed out from the connection of our hose to the customer fill line.  Driver said he shut down the truck first because he was right there and then closed the internal and external valve.  Not sure how much spilled but 100 gallons was estimated before the flow stopped.  it is most likely not that much, though, because the containment area holds 20-25 gallons.  It did not fill it but it did spray out on to the asphalt.  Driver was exposed to some mist, on his neck, under his face shield.  He immediately went to the eye wash station and then the shower.  He was looked at by a nurse onsite but there was no indication of any exposure.  We had a spill response company come in and clean up the spill.  It was determined that the gasket was missing in the hose adaptor.
column169: The driver did not follow proper procedure to ensure all gaskets were in place and everything was secure before starting the product flowing.  The driver no longer works for us.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: The driver was en route with a box trailer to deliver various chemicals to a customer.  While enroute, just prior to the customer facility, the driver recalls driving over a bump in the road.  The driver determined that the movement of the trailer was minor and continued to the customer facility, which was approximately 5 miles away.  Once at the loading dock, the driver inspected the load and identified that a pallet had been damaged and a nail was protruding from the pallet, which appeared to have damaged a drum containing Olympia 240 (a blend of sodium hydroxide and sodium hypochlorite).  After identifying the damaged drum, the release was contained and a storm sewer located near the loading dock was blocked to avoid the release from being discharged to the storm sewer.      It was determined that 263-pounds of the product were released from the damaged drum.  Based on the composition of the product, this equates to 39.5 pounds of sodium hydroxide and 13.2 pounds of sodium hypochlorite.  This is below the reportable quantity for each of these chemicals, which is 1,000 pounds and 100 pounds respectively.    In addition to containing and collecting the release, at the request of the customer facility, the area was further cleaned by a third party hazardous response crew (North Shore Environmental).  The area was pressure washed and the rinsate was collected for disposal.
column169: The supplier of the pallet that was damaged will be issued a “Supplier Corrective Action Request” to assist in the investigation.  In addition to the inspection of outgoing pallets already being completed, the pallets will be further scrutinized by employees who are being further trained regarding this incident to assist in identifying pallets that should not be used.

column42: AMINE, FLAMMABLE, CORROSIVE, N.O.S. OR POLYAMINES, FLAMMABLE, CORROSIVE N.O.S.
column168: Loaded tank car, TAMX 2000 - containing a class 3 flammable liquid, was discoverd to be leaking from the bottom of the car along track 12 of the UPRR Chicago Heights Railyard. Matthew Thompson, Hazardous Material Manager, responded to find product releasing from the top mounted flange, were the vavle connects to the sump/tank, of the bottom outlet valve. After further assessment it was found that the (8) flange bolts were insufficeintly tightened. The bolts were tightened and the released ceased.
column169: Prior to transportation inspect for proper securement of tank car. This includes all fittings, valves, and gaskets.

column168: Container ENHU 636711 was discovered to be releasing an unknown substance within the destination rail facility.  Billing indicated no hazardous materials, however, upon removing items from the container (3) steel drums, containing corrosive liquid n.o.s., were discovered. The material is classified as a class 8 material and over 1,001 lbs, which requires external placarding of the container.  The drums are found to be undeclared hazardous materials and billing would require updating prior to further transportation. Hazardous materials were not the cause of the release.
column169: Evaluate all bills of lading prior to preparing billing for rail transportation. The hazardous materials may not meet certain placarding requirements but still requires to be declared on railroad billing.

column168: Driver was headed north bound on Highway 59. The driver looked over to the passenger seat and was momentarily distracted. when he looked back at the road, his huit was veering off the left shoulder of the road. he was able to get the truck back onto the main lanes but his liguid load was sloshing side to side and he could not get it under control. He exited off the right hand shoulder of the road and the truck and trailer rolled onto it's side. The driver was uninjured and climbed out through the windshied. he lost his phone and could not call for help. Texas DPS and El Campo Texas Fire depatment arrived on scene and notice the leak coming from pressure relief valve.The leak was just a trickle. The leaked continued for approximately 4 hours and was then plugged with putty and tape. Aprroximately 37 liquid gallons of product was spilled. A back hoe was brought out and earthen barriers were dug approximately 50 yards north and south of the tractor and trailer. Tideport then called out Suncoast Resources to to complete the off load of the product onto another trailer. Suncoast Resources also completed the Clean Up and Remadiation Process.
column169: Tideport will complete remedial training for "Distrcted Driving" for all drivers at its next Safety Meeting Scheduled for 1-22-2012. Topics will texting and cell phones, but also include other distractios such as eating, drinking, tuning the radio, looking at maps and more. This traing will also be intergrated into Tideport's "New Driver Orientations" immediately.

column168: Driver completed pre-trip inspection and proceeded to hook trailer at 14:18 in Peoria, IL.  Driver left Peoria at 14:40 and proceeded to Decatur, IL.  At approximately 15:25, the driver turned on Route 51 south from I 74 east.  After driving approximately one mile, driver felt the trailer release from the 5th wheel traveling around 45 mph.  When the trailer legs hit the pavement they buckled, causing one leg to puncture tank, releasing Beverage Alcohol onto the pavement running into ditch.  Authorities and clean up crews were immediately notified.  Cleanup and tow crews lifted trailer to minimize/stop spill.  The duration of the spill was approximately 2 hours before crews were able to minimize.  The hole size on the trailer was approximately 5 inches long with a jagged tear.  The total amount spilled was 2159 gallons, with 413 gallons being recovered by spill crews.  Testing was conducted on remaining product leaching in soil in the nearby ditch.  We are awaiting cleanup instructions.
column169: After performing a lengthy investigation, mechanical testing, and cause analysis, it was determined that the driver did not follow proper proceedures in making sure that the trailer was adequately locked into the 5th wheel.  This incident has and will be covered in future safety meetings as well as future training sessions.

column168: At approximately 4:15 PM on Saturday December 29, 2012, a KCS employee noticed a strong odor (Methyl Mercaptan) emanating from the north end of track #6 in the Port Arthur yard. Appropriate notifications were made and KCS emergency responders were activated.    Opon arrival, KCS emergency responders investigated 3 tank cars (ACF 94845, TELX 95102, TELX 95365) that were percieved to be cause of odor. After snoop solution investigation, air monitoring verification, and tank car appurtenance tightness verification, it was determined none of the original 3 tank cars were cause of source leak. KCS emergency responders were demobilized from Port Arthurt Yard.    At approximately 9:50 PM additional odor was suspected to be coming from tank car ACFX 94870 or tank car NATX 60028 (both Methyl Mercaptan cars). Appropriate notifications were made and Arkema (origin) emergency responders activated.    *Both of these cars were also involved in a Non-Accidental Release (NAR) situation for KCS on 12/21/2012. The leak was detected on tank car NATX 60028 in the B end liquid valve stem packing. Arkema responders responded to leak, tightened packing 1/2 turn, reported to KCS the leak was stopped, and car was released. A properly operating valve would not have required the second tightening process to the packing.    At approximately 11:15 PM, Arkema emergency responders arrived on-site, contacted appropriate KCS personnel and began tank car assessment. Upon closer inspection of the 2 suspected tank cars, tank car NATX 60028 was found to be leaking in the same location as the 12/21/2012 NAR, in the B end liquid valve stem packing. The tank car was switched back to origin (Arkema) for off-loading and valve replacement.     In summation, the shipper offered the tank car with a defective tank car component, the shipper's emergency responders claimed securement of the defective tank car appurtenance, and the shipper offered the tank car without proper, true securement.    *No injuries throughout the entire incident were reported.    File Note Item 19-the quantity released was estimated. The actual amount released from this container is unknown to the carrier. To determine actual amount released: contact the offeror to determine actual quantity in tank car at origin (if available), then contact  consignee to determine actual amount in tank car once unloaded (if available), and the difference will be the total amount released.     File Note: Item 27-Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.
column169: Recommendations:    The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities,   and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence   of unsafe transportation conditions.    The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. To improve communications the shipper can provide contact information in this web site (Contact Network) to better facilitate incident response and post incident communications as applicable.

column168: Brief Summary of Alleged Incident: BMS driver reported that when he backed into the customer dock and went to the rear of the trailer, he noticed a large amount of bleach leaking out of the rear of the trailer. After the liquid flow subsided, the customer hazmat team opened the rear door and discovered the valve on their tote of Sodium Hypochlorite 12.5% had broken off of the tote and the contents had all spilled out.    Immediate Corrective Action Taken: The entire spill was contained in the customer's waste treatment system.  The customer's hazmat team deconned the tote and the inside rear of the trailer.  The driver returned the tote with the broken valve and the was emptied and throughly cleaned.  The leak did not affect any of the other freight on the truck.
column169: Based on the review by our investigation team, we estimate the nipple that joins the bottom valve to the inner tank of the tote had a stress fracture that finally released during movement of the truck.  The point of this fracture may have been in installation of the nipple/valve or in handling the tote if extra stress was placed on the valve after making a connection.  The failure was at the weakest point of the connection, where the nipple threads into the inner tank of the tote.      To prevent reoccurrence, we intend to install a brace at the bottom of the tote to support the dry-disconnect valve assembly.  Also, we are evaluating the use of a dedicated deep hex socket wrench to improve the installation of the nipple and valve.  A review of the tote handling process with applicable operators is recommended to ensure there are no steps that would place extra stress on the valve assembly.

On December 11, 2012, a release of UN1866 Resin Solution was discovered inside of a Landstar- Ranger tractor trailer. Approximately ¼ gallon of material was released to the trailer floor due to a crack in the drum. No storm drains, waterways, or soil were impacted as a result of this release. USES personnel arrived on site to perform the proper cleanup. USES personnel over-packed the leaking drum and performed the proper cleanup of the trailer. The over-packed drum was taken for disposal. All other waste was collected and containerized for proper transportation and disposal.

column168: On December 17, 2012, at approximately 1050 EST, two drums of UN1830 sulfuric acid leaked approximately 10 gallons of product on board a Vitran trailer. The release impacted the trailer floor and the nearby parking area. A small amount of product also dripped to the floor of a nearby school from an impacted pallet during delivery. No storm drains, waterways, or soils were impacted by the release. Environmental Management Specialists (EMS), arrived onsite to investigate and perform the proper cleanup. EMS personnel over-packed the leaking drums and neutralized the released acid. Granular absorbents were applied to the impacted areas and worked in thoroughly. All waste was collected and containerized for proper transportation and disposal.

column168: BioLab, Inc. requested services from Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc.  In particular, the transportation and disposal of certain waste streams (1248 containers of waste oxidizing solids N.O.S.) that are generated from BioLabs production of various products (i.e. pool supplies).     The waste was transported by trailer from BioLab’s facility to a facility located at 2300 Short Hillsboro, El Dorado AR pending final transportation to the intended waste management facility Clean Harbors Eldorado LLC for disposal.   At approximately 10:00 am on December 18, 2012 the trailer had arrived at this location, and later that same day at around 4:00pm a Clean Harbors employee noticed white smoke emanating from the rear door of the trailer containing BioLab’s waste.  The facility’s emergency response plan was activated and an emergency response team and a fire brigade (hereinafter “responders”) from the neighboring facility (Clean Harbors El Dorado LLC) arrived at the scene.  The response team and fire brigade after having assessed the situation determined that BioLab’s waste was reacting inside the trailer, it was also determined that no other trailers or individuals were involved, it was at this point that the responders initiated their response and control activities which involved the use of water cannons to cool the trailer and stop the reaction of BioLab’s waste.  In addition, the responders initiated containment activities to control the run-off from the response activities.      In conjunction with the local authorities the responders assisted in the evacuation of any individuals that could potentially come into contact with the smoke that emanating from the trailer.  The responder’s efforts resulted in the complete cessation of the reaction occurring with BioLab’s waste.  The responders stayed on site throughout the night to insure the reaction did not re-initiate and not further reactions occurred.      In addition to the responders and local authorities, representatives from the US EPA arrived on scene.  The EPA representatives conducted an initial air monitoring assessment and continued with follow-up assessments the following day and concluded that there were no off-site impacts.  Additionally the storm water run-off was assessed by the US EPA and again no off-site impacts were identified.      Once the site was secured, facility personnel repackaged the remnants of BioLab’s waste  where it was then transported to Clean Harbors El Dorado LLC where it was disposed via incineration.  The subject trailer was deconned, the water used to control the reaction was collected and placed into storage tanks pending analytical and disposal options.  Finally all cleanup debris including soil from the area where the trailer was parked was containerized and will be disposed of once analytical results are reviewed and a disposal method is determined.
column169: Prior to Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc.’s accepting Biolab’s waste for transport the containers holding said waste were visually inspected.  The inspection found no evidence that the shipment was not stable.  Likewise, the containers appeared to have been properly closed, marked, labeled and secured.  Based upon the foregoing inspections, as well as the representations made by BioLab’s the waste was accepted for transportation.      Although a cause and origin analysis was not performed, Clean Harbors’ initial findings have concluded that this incident appears to have been the result of an exothermic reaction within the containers that held Biolab’s waste on the subject trailer.  Clean Harbors’ initial findings have not uncovered anything that would contradict these findings, but it reserves the right to modify, alter, or amend its conclusions based upon newly discovered facts or information not previously available.  Additionally, the investigation remains ongoing as it seeks to involve the parties that may have through their acts or failure to act caused or contributed to the incident, but during this process the waste stream involved has been blocked from further shipment and disposal until such time as the investigation is complete and a determination has been made that additional safety measures could be instituted to reduce and/or preclude a like or similar incident.

column168: Entrained tank car PROX 15445 in an outbound BNSF train was reported with commodity wetness at the top fitting area. A BNSF mechanical responder vented the internal pressure from PROX 15445 which stopped additional commodity wetness from accumulating on the top of PROX 15445. The securement of valves and fittings were checked with no securement exceptions noted. Baking soda/water solution was applied to neutralize the spillage on the tank shell. A message to have PROX 15445 re-inspected at its next terminal location (Belen, NM) was initiated. Belen mechanical/hazardous material responders inspected PROX 15445 upon arrival and it was noted that commodity wetness was still present around the top valve fitting area. PROX 15445 was carefully set-out of the train and isolated in the railyard. No increase in commodity wetness was observed when PROX 15445 remained motionless. Further inspection by responders revealed a hairline crack at the liquid eduction line pipe flange weld. Spillage on the tank shell was neutralized. The commodity within PROX 15445 was transferred to another suitable tank car on 12/17/2012 without further incident. PROX 15445 is awaiting FRA OTMA for furtherance to a qualified repair facility.

column168: ON DECEMBER 18, 2012 CANEDA FOREST PRODUCT SALES LTD DRIVER LOADED 10 TOTES OF UN-1840 AT SHIPPER MINERAL RESEARCH & DEVELOPMENT 302 MIDWAY ROAD FREEPORT, TX 77541. THE DRIVER AND THE SHIPPER DISAGREED ON THE LOADING PATTERN OF THE TOTES. WHEN LOADED TO LEGALIZE THE AXLES FOR WEIGHT THIS LEFT A GAP BETWEEN THE TOTES. THE DRIVER SECURED THE TOTES WITH MULTIPLE LOAD STRAPS BETWEEN THE TOTES AS DOCUMENTED ON THE DRIVERS BOL. WHILE ENROUTE TO CALGARY, ALBERTA ON DECEMBER 20, 2012 IN THE STATE OF COLORADO, THE DRIVER WAS IN A SNOWSTORM AND A HARD BRAKE MANEUVER HAD TO BE APPLIED TO AVOID ANOTHER TRACTOR TRAILER THAT WAS PARKED ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD. VISIBILITY WAS VERY POOR.   A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED AT THE FORT COLLINS PORT OF ENTRY WHEN THE DRIVE AXLE WAS OVERWEIGHT DUE TO THE SHIFTING LOAD FROM THE HARD APPLIED BRAKES. THE HARD BRAKE MANEUVER ALSO STRESSED THE LOAD STRAPS AND BROKE ON WHICH PROPELLED THE BUCKLE INTO ONE OF THE TOTES. THIS CAUSED A SMALL PUNCTURE HOLE IN THE PLASTIC LINER.  ALL AUTHORITIES AND CANEDA FOREST PRODUCT SALES LTD SAFETY AND COMPLIANCE MANAGER WERE NOTIFIED AT 7:30 AM DECEMBER 20, 2012. LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT AND DOT HAZMAT SECURED THE SCENE. THE TRAILER HAD AN ALUMINUM FLOOR WHICH HELD THE PRODUCT WITHIN THE TRAILER WHILE AWAITING BELFOR ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND.  BELFOR CALLED SAFETY AND COMPLIANCE MANAGER FOR CANEDA FOREST PRODUCT SALES LTD AT 14:30. BELFOR USED A DYKE, PLASTIC LINER AND ABSORBANT TO CAPTURE THE PRODUCT UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS OF THE TRAILER. AT THIS TIME THE PUNCTURE WAS DISCOVERED. A NEW TOTE WAS SUPPLIED AND PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED OUT OF THE DAMAGED TOTE.  THE OLD TOTE WAS USED TO HOLD ALL OF THE ABSORBENT AND RAGS, THE TRAILER RELOADED AND SECURED.  AT THIS POINT COLORADO DOT HAZMAT WERE SATISFIED THAT ALL WAS CONTAINED CLEANED UP AND THE UNIT CARRIED ON ITS WAY TO CALGARY ALBERTA.
column169: ADDITIONAL LOAD SECUREMENT AND HAZMAT TRAINING WAS GIVEN TO THE DRIVER. THE DRIVER WAS WRITTEN UP FOR THE INCIDENT AND WILL ALSO BE INVOLVED GOING FORWARD IN HELPING TO TRAIN OTHER CANEDA FOREST PRODUCT SALES LTD DRIVERS. THE INCIDENT WAS BROUGHT UP IN THE MONTHLY CANEDA FOREST PRODUCT SALES LTD CONFERENCE CALL. INFORMATION EMAILS WERE SENT TO DISPATCH ABOUT HAZMAT AND LOAD SECUREMENT.THERE ARE CHANGES BEING MADE TO DRIVERS TRIP MANIFESTS THAT INCLUDE LOAD SECUREMENT EQUIPMENT AND SIGN OFF FROM DOCK EMPLOYEES AND DRIVERS AS A DOUBLE CHECK.  CANEDA FOREST PRODUCT SALES LTD IS ALSO SCHEDULING AN OUTSIDE HAZMAT TRAINER TO COME IN TO DO MORE TRAINING FOR DISPATCH AND DRIVERS.  POLICY IS GOING TO BE REINFORCED BY SAFETY AND COMPLIANCE MANAGER ON SENDING PROPER LOAD SECUREMENT EQUIPMENT WHEN GOING TO AREAS TO PICK UP HAZMAT.
column198: Caneda Forest Product Sales Ltd. DBA Caneda Transport Inc.

column168: ON DEC. 18, 2012 AT 14:49, I RECEIVED A CALL THAT OUR TRUCK #51 HAD ROLLED OVER AT MP 326 ON THE GEORGE PARKS HWY. I DISPATCHED A 5000G FUEL TRUCK (EMPTY) AND A CREW OF 3 MEN WITH SPILL RESPONSE EQUIP AND A TOWING AND RECOVERY VEHICLE TO THE SITE. UPON ARRIVAL WE FIRST CHECKED ON THE CONDITION OF OUR DRIVER TOM MCGEE, HE WAS HURTING IN HIS LOWER BACK BECAUSE OF THE ROLL OVER AND WAS TRANSFERRED TO FAIRBANKS MEMORIAL HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS EVALUATED AND RELEASED. WE LOOKED OVER THE TRUCK AND NOTICED A SMALL LEAK THAT WAS POINTED OUT TO US BY THE ALASKA STATE TROOPERS AND SECURED THE LEAK WITH A BRACE AGAINST THE DOME LID AND PLACE A BUCKET UNDER TO CATCH ANY FUEL THAT WAS CAPTURED IN BUCKET. A PUMP WAS PUT IN PLACE AND HOLES WERE DRILLED INTO TANK AND ALL FUEL WAS TRANSFERRED TO 5000G FUEL TRUCK THAT WAS DISPATCHED TO SCENE. AFTER BEING EMPTIED, CABLES AND CHAINS WERE HOOKED TO OVERTURNED TANK TRUCK AND WAS RIGHTED AND PULLED TO ROADWAY WHERE IT WAS INSPECTED AND THEN TOWED TO THE ALASKA AEROFUEL YARD IN FAIRBANKS AND PLACE IN HEATED GARAGE TO INSPECT.    THE DEPTH OF THE SNOW WAS WELL OVER 4' DEEP WHERE SPILL OCCURRED AND RECOVERY OF FUEL WAS IMPOSSIBLE AS IT WAS NOT OVER A LARGE AREA BUT RATHER A SINGLE DRIPPING AND SNOW WAS NOT SATURATED WITH FUEL.
column169: BECAUSE OF THE LOCATION OF THE ROLLOVER (AT THE CREST OF A HILL ON FLAT GROUND) DRIVER INDICATED BECAUSE OF THE LONG PULL TO THE TOP, WHEN HE ARRIVED HE WAS ONLY TRAVELING 30 MPH. ROAD NARROWS AT THAT POINT AND HE INDICATED THAT HE PULL OVER BECAUSE OF ANOTHER TRACTOR TRAILER APPROACHING THE DESCENT WAS CROWDING THE CENTER OF THE ROAD AN SO HE MOVED TO THE RIGHT AND HIS OUTER STEERING CAUGHT THE BERM AND WAS SUCKED IN THAN CAUSING ROLLOVER. ALL DRIVERS ARE INSTRUCTED IN TAKING CAUTION IN DRIVING DAILY, ESPECIALLY SINCE THE LATEST SNOW FALL.

column168: Tank car CTCX 732392 in the railyard was reported dripping commodity from the bottom outlet valve area. Absorbent pads and a catch receptacle were placed under CTCX 732392 and it was cordoned-off in the railyard. Local mechanical responders reported tool tightening the bottom outlet closure cap (BOC) by 1 1/2 turns which stopped the commodity drips. All observed ground spillage evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: A strong sulfur odor was reported in the bowl tracks in the railyard. This area was cordoned-off which also ceased rail operations at this locale until the odor source was determined and eliminated. Response contractors with air monitoring and chemical detection equipment located the odor source at tank car AMOX 13146 standing in the bowl tracks.  No liquid commodity release was observed. Responders found two manway securement swing bolt nuts less than tool tight on AMOX 13146. After the manway securement nuts were properly tool tightened and secured, the vapor/odor release from AMOX 13146 ceased. This was verified by the detection/sensor equipment utilized by the responders. AMOX 13146's side specification stencil displayed last tank qualification in year 2004.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: An inbound BNSF train's mechanical inspection in the railyard revealed entrained tank car ADMX 29681 dripping commodity from its bottom outlet valve (BOV) area. ADMX 29681 was deemed safe to move and was set-out from the train for further inspection. Inspection revealed the drip source was at the BOV mounting flange connection of the closed BOV. A response contractor tool tightened all BOV mounting flange bolt nuts that were found only hand tight or finger loose. After the BOV mounting flange securement was finalized, commodity drips ceased. ADMX 29681 continued to be monitored and no further commodity drips were detected. All spillage evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: As a result of the tote being moved, we beleive the seam on the tote cracked or outer metal frame intruded in the plastic due to the pressure /  weight of the material inside the packaging. It is a very slow leak coming from in between the bottom aluminum support plate and the actual bottom part of the plastic tank.......no visibility to that area, however no damage either nor any where around the leakin area.  The shipment did not leak en-route to us as the floor of the trailer it arrived on is clean so it started leaking and or the packaging failed when it was picked up and transported.  Amount released was clean up in-house upon discovery.

12/3/2012: During routine patrol of Conrail's Port Richmond Yard, Philadelphia, PA, NS PD Special Agent H. Dobbs noted tank car TILX 195950, load, Alcohols NOS, leaking from the top of the car.  S.A. Dobbs notified CR Risk Manager A. Richter, who in turn notified emergency response contractor Hepaco-React to respond and inspect.    Hepaco-React's G. Bunker responded, finding leak originating from underneath the breadbox/protective housing on top of the car.  Breadbox was still sealed at time of his inspection, bearing seals "ADM Decatur #702350" and "ER+R Mounds IL #0009310".  Seals broken, housing opened and found the 2" liquid line valve fully open and closure plug for same less than hand tight. column168: Approx. 0830 on Thursday 12/20/2012 at Parker-Hannifin in Woburn MA, Clean Harbors chemists packaged bags of aluminum powder submerged into 2 five gallon pails with 4 gallons of mineral oil each. With the 5 gallon pails sealed they were overpacked into a 30 gallon open head steel drum and packed with vermiculite then sealed for transportation by 1030am.  At 11:30am the chemists noticed the drum had bulged, and were off-gassing. Facility personell,Woburn Fire Dept, Mass DEP and Clean Harbors management were notified. The chemists moved the box truck to an isolated section of the parking lot. Woburn Fire arrived along with the Mass DEP a short time later At approx. 1220, the Woburn Fire Dept. started taking temperature readings from the drum, and every 15 or so there after.  Throughout the time span, the temp continued to drop, and the drum stopped off gassing.  The chemists donned the proper PPE with respirators and restabilize the aluminum powder with brand new mineral oil and repackaged the material for continued transportation to it intended disposal facility. The drums were continually monitored and the Mass DEP Rep and the Woburn FD Capt. were satisfied and happy with the end result, and had no further remarks or questions and explained the incident would be treated as a "complaint", and no further action was requested. Mass DEP Report# NE-20127495
column169: Clean Harbors conducted an internal review of the incident and concluded that moisture was likly present in the mineral oil initially applied to the aluminum powder which caused the reaction. A Clean Harbors review team evaluated several options to minimize the handling of mineral oil and the potential for the introduction of moisture into secondary containers. The following Clean Harbors Standard Operating Procedure (SOP)will be re-written to reflect the following changes; 1)Mineral Oil will be transferred onto one gallon containers which will be sealed until ready to use. 2)Chemist will use multiple one gallon containers, as needed, for field operations. 3)One gallon containers will be single use, and will not be re-filled after use. 4) Any unused residual mineral oil in containers from field operations will not be reused at other sites and be properly disposed of.

On December 19, 2012 at approximately 12:30 PM CST,  R9747119 derailed two tank cars while performing switching operations between Taminco Storage Yard and the Evergreen Lead, St. Gabriel, LA. The crew made several switching moves towards both tracks before kicking 9 cars against 12 standing cars with 7 handbrakes applied. Impact derailed TILX 319655 (Load) puncturing the tank car and also derailed TILX 316860 (Residue). The contents of TILX 319655 were completely released onto the ground in Taminco's Storage yard.     There were no exposures or injuries to the CN train crew, but three Taminco employees reported injuries due to the uncontrolled release of product. The Taminco employees reporting injuries at the time of the incident included two (2) product inhalation, treated at the local hospital and released to return to duty, one (1) product vapor / mist exposure to skin, held overnight at the local hospital and released to duty.    TILX 316860 will be cleaned, purged of product and an OTMA applied for to move to a repair facility.

column168: Incident Description:    0115 December 23, 2012    Harris Transportation driver Saul Perez arrived on Valero site 4123. At this time Saul verified delivery address and calculated that the entire load would fit. He then set up for his delivery and began delivery of the "midgrade" gasoline. While delivering the midgrade,Saul then set up the "regular" grade delivery. Saul then opened the delivery valve on the truck partially  to look for any leaks. He observed no leaks, so he opened the delivery valve "full" open. It was at this time Saul instantly realized that the "ears" (the locking mechanism) had come open at the fitting-end on the tank. Saul then immediately shut down the flow of fuel to the regular tank. He placed absorbent material around the storm drain, manhole,as well as protecting the area keeping any product from heading toward the station building itself.    Frankie Fortine,the night attendant at the station,called The Littleton Fire & Rescue. Littleton Fire and Rescue Department arrived on site within  20 minutes or less of the initial call from Frankie Fortine.    They spread additional absorbents and "kitty  litter" to pick up any remaining product on the concrete. The entire spilled product was contained on the delivery site's property.  The fire department then issued an Order of Cleanup. They estimated the release to be approximately in the area of 50- 100 gallons.     Weather:    At the time of the spill,it was approximately 30 degrees Fahrenheit, dry, and there was no water on the ground.    0130 December 23,2012    Harris driver Saul Perez notified Harris dispatch of the spill and Harris Dispatch began the notification process within Harris.    The following people were notified:    Craig Watkins, CO Area Manager:  Chuck Snook,Emergency Responder: Matt Haley,CO Field Safety Supervisor: Christie Sanders,Safety & Risk:  Jan Frost, Operations  Mgr.: Tracy Rich,Denver Dispatch: Loretta Wade, Dispatch Mgr.:(503) 522-9353 (206) 510-8908 (971) 201-7262 (503) 475-1947 (503) 552-5827 (503) 552-5815(503)552-5815     At this time, Chuck Snook called BELFOR Environmental (Harris' environmental contactor) for the cleanup response. Matt Haley contacted Victor Stanley, a senior driver in our Denver terminal, to go on site and assist Saul Perez and all of the Responders with the cleanup.    0430 December 23, 2012    BELFOR Environmental arrived on the scene with Supervisor Pete Alvara do,Hazmat Technicians Truitt Hart,and Slavador Mendoza.They began picking up the oil dry absorbent that was placed by the fire department and Harris. The cleanup materials were placed in (2) drums from the total cleanup.
column169: 0630 December 23,2012    BELFOR Environmental had finished the cleanup about 0630 and along with everyone else left the site shortly thereafter. According to the report from BELFOR, and verbal confirmation from Mark Churchill, Senior Project Manager with BELFOR Environmental,none of the spilled product reached the storm drain at any time; all product was contained on site.    On December 27, 2012,Mark Taylor with BELFOR delivered the drums under the Uniform Hazardous Waste Manifest tl 005660911to AET Environmental for disposal at Rineco in Bento, AR on UHWM.    After reviewing the incident,Area Manager, Craig Watkins,placed Saul Perez "off  duty" until Saul completes a Delivery Recertification Training process to insure that he fully understands the impact of the "Triple Check" process in preventing future incidents.  Retraining will be completed by a Certified Trainer and approved  by Harris management before Saul will be able to return to work.    Prepared by: Christie Sanders,Safety & Risk

column168: OUR DRIVER {TRACY ESPLIN) ON DECEMBER 12,2012 WENT TO WORK AT ABOUT 4:00P.M.    HE WENT TO CEDAR CITY HOLLEY TERMINAL AND LOADED FOR ST. GEORGE,UT. HE MADE THAT DELIVERY WITH NO PROBLEMS. HE THEN WENT FROM ST.GEORGE TO CEDAR CITY TERMINAL  AND LOADED FOR HIS LAST LOAD OF HIS SHIFT TO LA VERKIN,UT. HE WENT ABOUT 20 MILES OUTSIDE CEDAR CITY AND HIS TRAILER GOT OFF THE SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY. HE OVER CORRECTED HIS POWER UNIT TO BRING IT BACK ON TO THE ROAD. THE TRAILER ROLLED OVER CAUSING THE TRUCK TO LAYOVER ON IT'S SIDE. THE DRIVER WAS NOT INJURED.    THE TRUCK DID NOT LOSE ANY PRODUCT,NOTHING  RUPTURED. THE TRAILER ROLLED COMPLETELY OVER CAUSING THE ONE DOME LID TO GET MASHED AND BEGIN TO LEAK. SOME OF THE TRAILERS PIPES UNDER THE TRAILER ALSO LEAKED.    THE HIGHWAY PATROL WAS CALLED ALONG WITH THE CEDAR CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT. I WAS NOTIFIED AND CALLED ENVIRO CARE AN E.P.A. COMPANY THAT WE USE TO CLEAN UP ANY SPILLS. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT FOAMED THE WHOLE UNIT DOWN AND THEN THEY BEGAN TO STOP THE LEAKS. WE LOST ABOUT 3963 GALLONS OF GASOLINE UNLEADED {UN1203). THE FIREMEN BUILT AND DIKED THE FUEL. THE FUEL DID NOT GET INTO ANY DITCHES OR WATER WAYS. WE ALSO CALLED A TRANSPORT COMPANY TO PUMP THE PRODUCT OUT OF THE TRUCK AND TRAILER.THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WAS ON IT'S SIDE FOR ABOUT 6 HOURS.
column169: THE EQUIPMENT WAS ONLY ABOUT 1 YEAR OLD AND WAS IN GOOD WORKING ORDER. THE DRIVER PASSED THE D.O.T. 5 PANEL DRUG TEST,BUT FAILED THE NINE PANEL PERSCRIPTION DRUG TEST. HE WAS CITED FOR IMPAIRED DRIVING.    WE ARE GOING TO MAKE A COMPANY POLICY TO RANDOMLY TEST.    NOT ONLY D.O.T. 5 PANEL (WHICH WE HAVE ALWAYS DONE) BUT ALSO TEST THE NINE PANEL TEST. WE WOULD ALSO LIKE TO HAVE THE DRIVER SIGN OFF AS HE DOES HIS PRE TRIP INSPECTIONS ON HIS TRUCK UNIT, TO ALSO SIGN OFF ON HIS PHYSICAL WELLNESS, BEFORE HE STARTS HIS SHIFT. (I HAVE JJ KELLER WORKING WITH ME ON THIS ISSUE.) IS HE FEELING WELL,DOES HE HAVE A COLD. IS HE TAKING ANY MEDICATION BECAUSE HE DOESN'T FEEL WELL, ETC.    WE WOULD LIKE TO IMPLEMENT IN OUR COMPANY POLICY THAT WE RANDOMLY TEST FOR 9 PANEL DRUGS AND AT LEAST TWICE  PER YEAR TEST EVERY DRIVER ON THIS NINE PANEL TEST.    IT WILL TAKE SOME COMPANY POLICY CHANGES,BUT I BELIEVE IT WILL BE WORTH IT..

column168: VEHICLE WAS TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON COUNTY ROAD 35. VEHICLE CAME INTO A LFET TURN AND WAS SWINGING WIDE TO ALLOW REAR OF TRAILER TO REMAIN ON THE ROAD. THE TRACTOR SLIPPED OFF RIGHT EDGE OF THE ROAD WHICH WAS SNOW COVERED AND SLID OFF THE BANK AND ROLLED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE. THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE OF THE CARGO. IT LAID QUITE SOFTLY INTO THE SNOW CAUSING VERY LITTLE DAMAGE TO TRAILER. THE DRIVER CALLED ON HIS CELL TO HIS TERMINAL MANAGER AND 911 AND THE COLORADO STATE PATROL ARRIVED ON THE SCENE. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LOAD WOULD HAVE TO BE TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER COMPANY TRUCK SO THE STATE PATROL CALLED THE CRAIG FIRE DEPT. WHICH INCLUDED THEIR HAZMAT EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO HELP IN THE TRANSFER. THE TEAM DRILLED 4 INCH HOLES IN THE UPPER SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND COMPANY PERSONNEL PUT HOSES INTO THE TRAILER AND TRANSFERRED THE OIL TO THE WAITING VEHICLE. IT WAS UP-RIGHTED BY TWO WRECKER UNITS FROM MEEKER.
column169: IN REVIEWING THIS INCIDENT AND WITH PAST EXPERIENCE, THE COUNTY ROADS DURING THE COLD AND SNOWY SEASON ARE VERY DANGEROUS AND EXTRA CAUTION NEEDS TO BE TAKEN WHEN DRIVING ON THEM. MANY TIMES WHEN THE COUNTY ROADS ARE GRADED TO REMOVE SNOW, THE EDGE OF THE ROADS BECOMES DIFFICULT TO SEE BECAUSE THE MOTOR GRADER FILLS UP THE BAR DITCH WITH SNOW AND THE ROAD LOOK WIDER THAN IT REALLY IS. AS THE SAFETY DEPT. A MEMO WILL BE SENT TO ALL DRIVERS WARNING OF THIS DANGER.

column168: Sometime between 12/24/2012 and 12/25/2012, a trespasser gained access into the Dana Transport facility where multiple tankers were staged.  The trespasser maliciously opened valves on numerous tanks on site causing the tanks to leak their contents onto the ground and eventually affecting a tributary of Paw Creek.  The vandal had broken the seals on valve caps, then opened all valves releasing the material.  Of all containers affected, only one possessed a DOT classified hazardous material (UN2789 Acetic Acid).  The other affected tanks contained non hazardous car wash waxes and mineral oils.      The release was found early morning ~0700 on 12/25/12 when a Dana employee stopped by the facility.      NRC report number 1034146 was assigned to this incident however a report is not available as this is considered a criminal act.      Once the release had been found, Dana personnel contacted E.R.T.S. to conduct necessary reporting and to dispatch a response contractor to begin cleanup operations.
column169: Root Cause / Corrective Action efforts have been conducted. Express Container Services, operator of the site, has installed surveillance cameras. The Dana Transport companies are investigating alternative means to secure the hydraulic pump that operates cargo tank internal valves. A site-specific security assessment was conducted and the existing Site-Specific Security Plan is being revised to address how preloaded cargo tanks are staged short-term at this facility. All company locations have also conducted site-specific security assessments and their Security Plans are being reviewed and/or revised at this time.

column168: MAVERIK DRIVER (TIM LAVERS)ON DECEMBER 26,2012. WENT TO WORK ABOUT 17:00 HOURS AND LOADED IN BILLINGS MONTANA, AT THE EXXON TERMINAL. HE LOADED ONE OF OUR CODY, WYOMING STORES. AS HE STARTED DOWN  BELFREY HWY 120 NORTH. IT BEGAN TO SNOW. THERE WAS ABOUT 2 INCHES OF SNOW WHEN HE GOT ABOUT 12 MILES NORTH WEST OF CODY AND RAN  HIS TRAILER TO CLOSE TO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD OVER CORRECTED AND ROLLED HIS TRAILER ABOUT 21:15 HOURS. THE TRUCK DID NOT TURN OVER.    HIGHWAY PATROL WAS NOTIFIED THEY CALLED A WRECKER. OUR COMPANY WAS NOTIFIED AND WE CALLED OUR INSURANCE COMPANY AND THE HEALTH DEPARTMENT. THE DRIVER NOTICED THAT THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE PEPCOCK THAT IS BETWEEN THE BULK HEADS. THE MIDDLE BULK HEAD HAD RUPTURED AS THE TRAILER TURNED OVER . THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CAME AND PLUGGED THE PEPCOCK WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  WE DISPATCHED A COMPANY TO COME AND PUMP OFF THE TRAILER. BECAUSE OF THE STORM, THEY DIDN'T GET THERE UNTIL THE NEXT MORNING. THEY PUMPED OFF THE TRAILER AND THAT PRODUCT WAS DELIVERED TO OUR POWEL, WY.STORE. THE TRUCK WAS NOT DAMAGED AND DELIVERED HIS LOAD TO CODY, WY. STORE.    HANSER'S A ENVIRONMENTAL AND REMEDIATION COMPANY WAS CALLED AND HANDLED THE CLEAN  -UP OF THE FUEL SPILL.
column169: THE WEATHER HAD A FACTOR IN THIS ACCIDENT.I BELIEVE THE DRIVER COULD NOT SEE WHAT LANE HE WAS IN AND GOT TO CLOSE TO THE SHOULDER OF THE ROAD. WE HAD TRAINING ON THIS  LAST MAY AND THIS DRIVER WAS THEIR. I HAVE GOT WITH J.J KELLER AND OUR INSURANCE COMPANY TO LOOK AT A QUARTERLY TRAINING  PROGRAM WHERE TRAINING IS A PRIORITY WITH All DRIVERS. THIS DRIVER HAS TEN YEARS OF EXSPERIENCE DRIVING BUT DIFFERENT SITUATIONS ARISE AND HE WAS CAUGHT OFF GUARD AND MISTAKES HAPPEN.    I WAS SURPRISED THAT THE TRAILER ONLY LEAKED OUT OF ONE PEPCOCK. WE ARE THINKING ABOUT PUTIING A V-KNECKED WOODEN DAULIN EACH TRUCK TO STOP SUCH LEAKS. THE DRIVER HAD NOTHING TO PUT IN THIS PEPCOCK UNTIL THE FIRE DEPARTMENT GOT THEIR.      TRAINING, TRAINING AND MORE TRAINING IS OUR TOP PRIORITY.

column168: The contents of the tank car were being transfered to a in-house storage tank using air pressure.  The cam-loc clamp mechanism holding the transfer hose to the tank car came loose causing the acid to spill.  Most of the acid was captured in the containment area under the tank car but a portion spilled on to an asphalt surface outside the containment structure.  At no time did any of the acid come into contact with the bare ground or the storm water collection system.  Acid inside the containment area was sent to our onsite, permitted wastewater treatment system.  Acid outside the containment area was neutralized with calcium carbonate and then sent to the mill's wastewater treatment plant.
column169: More secure methods to attach the transfer hose to the tank car are being investigated.  At present a locking mechanism has been added to the cam-loc to prevent it from coming loose during the transfer process.

column168: The package was unloaded with leakage noted on the box.  Examination of the inner container revealed that the container(s) had loose cap(s) and leaked.  The leakage was contained.  The cap(s) were secured.  The carton was wet but otherwise undamaged.  The undamaged portion of the package was repacked for return to shipper.

Transport delivery unit was connected to the bulk storage tank and was in the process of off-loading. The driver failed to notice that the brakes on the transport had not set and that the unit was in a neutral position. With the vibration of the liquid pump off-loading, the vehicle began to roll forward. The hoses were attached and began to stretch. At the maximum distance of the hoses, the piping on the bulk stantion failed by design and the emergency shut-offs reacted. All valves were shut by design and the release was contained. The driver ran forward of the vehicle and jumped into the moving truck cab. He applied the foot pedal and properly set the parking brakes. Due to the release of product, the district initiated an emergency evacuation and contacted local authorities for an emergency response. The gas cloud dissipated and the situation was under controled. Local and state authorities inspected the transport and discovered a faulty air value. The unit was placed out of service and repaired. The bulk storage was repaired and returned to service.

column168: 12-26-12 Upon arrival at the facility, a transfer from the railcar to an on-site storage tank was initiated. During the transfer, a tankwagon was being loaded in the same vicinity as the unloading process. At the completion of filling the tankwagon, the operator was going up the stairs to button up the tankwagon. At this point, he witnessed ferric starting to leak out of the rail car between our fitting and the fitting on the car. He shut down the transfer and released the air pressure on the railcar. He then C clamp on the fittings to slow down the leak. He then re-tightened the bolts on the fittings to stop the leak. A call to the company incident commander was then initiated. Duration of the release was approximately 5 minutes. During the investigation, it was discovered that a tear had occurred on the gasket.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1135 HOURS ON 12/16/2012 A FOREMAN OF PAN AM RAILWAYS STOPPED THE TRAIN DUE TO WHAT APPEARED TO BE A LEAK COMING FROM UNDERNEATH OF THE RAIL CAR TILX 191906. UPON INSPECTION OF THE RAIL CAR AT MILE POST 8 ON THE ROTTERDAM BRANCH MAIN LINE. PAN AM RAILWAYS FOREMAN DESCRIBED THE LEAK AS A SMALL DRIBBLE COMING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE. THE VALVE LEVER WAS FACING DOWNWARD A BIT AND THE PIN THAT SECURES IT THE LEVER IN THE UPRIGHT POSITION WAS MISSING. A PAN AM RAILWAYS SUPERVISOR ON SITE CONTAINED THE LEAK WITH A BUCKET AND PLACED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE LEVER BACK INTO THE UPRIGHT POSITION STOPPING THE LEAK. THE SUPERVISOR THEN SECURED THE VALVE LEVER WITH A PIECE OF WIRE ASSURING THAT THE LEVER WILL NOT FALL DOWNWARD. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON SCENE AND AGREED WITH THE TEMPORARY SOLUTION TO KEEP THE LEVER IN THE UPRIGHT POSITION AND RELEASED THE TRAIN.

column62: Missing Component or Device; Human Error; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Procedures
column168: The loaded trailer 518 had been at a Tank Wash facility awaiting delivery and was connected to live steam to heat the Resin Solution in the trailer. The trailer had been at the Tank Wash for several days awaiting delivery. The Tank Wash uses a temperature probe that is inserted into the taller through a washout opening. Their procedure was to insert the probe long enough to measure the temperature and then remove it and replace the washout cap. A worker thinking that they were saving time removed the front washout cap, inserted the probe and left it there. At the end of their shift they did not communicate this and the next worker that then took the readings from the center washout using another probe. This worker was unaware of the temperature probe in the front washout or that it was unsecure. When the driver arrived to transport the trailer for delivery the trailer was disconnected from the steam and a final temperature reading was taken by the Tank Wash worker In the presence of the driver. As the driver began climbing atop the trailer the Tank Wash worker stopped the driver to tell them that they had secured the trailer and it was ready to go. The driver then completed his pre-trip and departed. On a hill two blocks from his delivery location the driver saw from his mirrors the resin material come out of the front washout of the trailer. The driver stopped and climbed atop of the trailer to find the Tank Washes temperature probe still in the front washout. The driver removed the probe, secured the washout and then continued the two blocks to the customer. With the temperature being colder the majority of the resin as adhered to the sides of the trailer with droplets of resin quarter to half dollar size that dripped off the trailer onto the roadway and parking lot. The customer notified local authorities. The local Fire Department and Environmental personnel responded and left the scene shortly after evaluating the situation and being satisfied with the cleanup efforts that were performed by plant personnel and Pettit Environmental Inc. of Louisville, KY. The waste collected was disposed by the plant through their hazardous waste program.
column169: Tank Wash has changed their policies to include:  The use of a checklist has been added. Temperature Probes will not be left on trailers or containers. The Probe will be inserted at the center clean out port (trailers) air Inlet (containers) only. While In attendance the Probe will be placed for 10 minutes to ensure an accurate reading. Remind the driver to inspect the top of the trailer to ensure it is secure. First Choice Logistics have reinforced their policy: The driver will always be responsible to perform the final inspection to ensure that all ports, caps, valves and manholes are secure prior to transporting. Auditing of the corrective actions are performed the TW and FCL

column168: At approximately 7:20 a.m. on December 1, 2012, a release of approximately 25 gallons of ultra-low sulfur No. 2 fuel oil occurred via an overfill during the delivery of oil by Global to a 1,000 gallon UST at the Site. The release occurred when the oil exited a vent pipe which was located adjacent to an exterior wall in a doorway and impacted a vending machine located below the vent pipe, as well as the concrete sidewalk.  The oil migrated from the release area to the east along the sidewalk and below the curbing to Boylston Street which separates the sidewalk from the street to the catch basin (CB-1) located approximately 40 feet east of the vent pipe on the corner of Hereford and Boylston Streets. Approximately one to two gallons of oil entered the catch basin before the spill was contained via absorbent material (i.e., Speedy-Dry®) initially by the driver of the Global delivery truck.    Clean Horbors Inc (CHI) arrived to the Site at 9:30 a.m. to perform response actions.  CHI removed the cover of the affected catch basin, CB-1.  Less than one-quarter inch of oil was observed on top of the water within the catch basin. The oil was below the invert elevation of the outfall pipe leading out of CB-1 to the downgradient catch basin, CB-2. Absorbent pads were placed in the bottom of CB-1 by CHI and then removed after the oil/water mixture became absorbed to the pads. Absorbent pads were also used to plug the downgradient pipe prior to deploying the absorbent pads to remove the oil/water mixture from CB-1. Environemntal Compliance Services (ECS) inspected CB-2; no staining was observed around the catch basin as it was not located within the spill pathway. In addition, no liquid (petroleum or water) was observed within  CB-2; only wet leaves and debris were present.  A bailer was used to confirm that no oil or petroleum sheen was present in either CB-1 or CB-2. A four gas meter was used to screen CB-1 and CB-2 for explosive vapors. No readings above background were recorded.      At approximately 10:00 a.m., CHI also swept up and removed the Speedy-Dry® that was present in the release area (the sidewalk, curb, and street). The absorbent material was placed in 55-gallon drums. CHI then applied an oil emulsion surfactant to the sidewalk and curb area to assist in further removing the oil residue from the paved areas and also from the cracks of the pavement along the curb. Additional absorbent pads were then applied to remove the product.     The condition of the catch basin was monitoried over the next few days to ensure that there was no residual product in the system
column169: The overfill was due to a combination of the customer placing an order for more than the tank could hold and a weak vent whistle that did not alert the driver to the potenital overfill situation.  The Fire Department was notifified of the situation.

column168: At approximately 0510 hrs, while preparing to start an ethanol transfer from railcar to tanker truck, the Kinder Morgan employee executing the transfer noted that ethanol was spilling from the mobile pump/transfer unit's strainer box. The ethanol pump was positioned for service after having a preventive maintenance procedure performed (3rd Party) and the pump had not been charged or ran since the work was performed. Initially the quantity released was reported as 20 gls (impacting pavement), it was later updated to <10 gls. Agency notifications were made to the NRC and CA Emergency Mgmt Agency (CEMA) - #s 1033880 and 12-7786.
column169: - Spill was cleaned up with spill kit/absorbent materials on-site and is currently awaiting transfer off-site via approved waste disposal contractor.  -A comprehensive discussion/training was conducted with the 3rd party maintenance company (T&S) in regards to the critical leak points on the pumps.  -A revision will be made to the SOP, requiring two pump operators observing the initial hook up, charging the lines and ensuring all systems are functioning correctly (positioning one loader at the pump while the second operator opens the BV valve). This procedure would be in place for all pumps returning to service.

column168: DRIVER MADE DELIVERY TO THE K&H COOPERATIVE CARDIROL IN BUFFALO CENTER, IA. HE PUT 70.1 GALS IN A METERED DELIVERY DOWN THE MONITOR OPENING INSTEAD OF THE DELIVERY RECEPTABLE. A SALEMAN FAMILIAR WITH THE SITE HEARD ABOUT THE DRIVER, THE DRIVER PUTTING FUEL DOWN THE WRONG PIPE INCORRECTLY ASSUMED WE HAD PUT IT DOWN A MONITORING WELL AT THIS LOCATION. THE SALESMAN NEVER WENT OUT TO THE LOCATION TO INVESTIGATE DUE TO A SEPARATE INCIDENT WITH THE COOP. WE RESPONDED APPROPRIATELY PER IA DNR'S TOM COLLINS INSTRUCTIONS AND DISCOVERED WHILE ON SCENE THAT OUR DRIVER DID NOT PUT THE 70 GALS DOWN THE TEST WELL, BUT DOWN THE PAN USED FOR THE MONITOR.

column168: UNIT WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON SR 443 AT INTERSECTION WITH NEW PHILADELPHIA RD. DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO TURN LEFT ONTO NORTHBOUND NEW PHILADELPHIA ROAD. AS THE UNIT ENTERED THE NORTHBOUND LANE OF NEW PHILADELPHIA RD. IT BEGAN TO TIP AND ROLLOVER AND CAME TO REST ON THE TOP OF THE CARGO TANK. THE MOST PROBABLE EXPLANATION FOR THE LEAKED PRODUCT IS THAT THE LOADING HATCH DUE TO THE FORCE OF THE ACCIDENT WAS FORCED AJAR JUST ENOUGH FOR THE PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT. THIS HATCH WAS ALSO LOCKED USING A STANDARD PADLOCK. SINCE THE ENTIRE WEIGHT OF THE TRUCK END TANK WERE RESTING ON THIS, THE ADDED HEIGHT FROM THE LOCK MAY ALSO HAVE BEEN A CONTRIBUTING FACOTR IN FORCING THE HATCH AJAR. HOWEVER, THE LOCK REMAINED INTACT AND MAY HAVE HELPED IN PREVENTING THE HATCH FROM OPENING COMPLETELY. THE WEIGHT OF THE REMAINING PRODUCT ALSO PROBABLY CONTRIBUTED TO FORCING THE PRODUCT OUT. THE PRODUCT PROBABLY CONTINUED TO LEAK AS LONG AS THE TANK REMAINED ON IT'S TOP. THE CONSISTENCY OF THE PRODUCT AND THE SMALL AMOUNT THAT THE HATCH WAS AJAR LIMITED THE SPILL. ALSO, AS SOON AS THE TRUCK WAS ROLLED TO IT'S SIDE THE HATCH RETURNED TO IT'S PROPER ALIGNMENT AND THE LEAKING STOPPED. THE LEAKING PRODUCT WAS CONFINED TO AN AREA UNDER THE TANK AND WAS INACCESSIBLE UNTIL THE TRUCK WAS RIGHTED. THE TANK ITSELF REMAINED FULLY INTEGRAL. THE LEAKED PRODUCT WAS THEN ABLE TO BE SHOVELED UP AND PLACED INTO BARRELS AND RETURNED TO OUR STORAGE FACILITY IN TAMAGUE, PA FOR EVENTUAL DISPOSITION. SEE INCLUDED PHOTOS
column169: ADDITIONAL DRIVER TRAINING PARTICULARLY AS PERTAINS TO ROLLOVER PREVENTION I.E., CORNERING, SPEED MANAGEMENT. VEHICLE DESIGN - THIS VEHICLE HAD A PARTICULARLY HIGH CENTER OF GRAVITY. THE TANK WAS MOUNTED ON A CHASSIS NOT WALL SUITED FOR IT'S FUNCTION. POTENTIALLY SOME GREATER PROTECTION EXCEEDING THE HEIGHT OF THE HATCH, IT'S COMPONENTS AND A LOCK SUCH WAS USED IN THE INSTANCE COULD BE DESIGNED AROUND THE HATCH. ROAD DESIGN - IT IS HIGHLY LIKELY THAT THE ROAD DESIGN AT THE INTERSECTION WHERE THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED CONTRIBUTED TO THE ROLLOVER. ALTHOUGH ROAD DESIGN IS GENERALLY OUT OF OUR CONTROL, ROUTES USED ARE AND SHOULD BE REVIEWED.

column168: TRANSPORT DELIVERY UNIT WAS CONNECTED TO THE BULK STORAGE TANK AND WAS IN THE PROCESS OF OFF-LOADING. THE DRIVER FAILED TO NOTICE THAT THE BRAKES ON THE TRANSPORT HAD NOT SET AND THAT THE UNIT WAS IN A NEUTRAL POSITION. WITH THE VIBRATION OF THE LIQUID PUMP OFF-LOADING, THE VEHICLE BEGAIN TO ROLL FORWARD. THE HOSES WERE ATTACHED AND BEGAN TO STRETCH. AT THE MAXIMUM DISTANCE OF THE HOSES, THE PIPING ON THE BULK STATION FAILED BY DESIGN AND THE EMERGENCY SHUT-OFFS REACTED. ALL VALVES WERE SHUT BY DESIGN AND THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED. THE DRIVER RAN FORWARD OF THE VEHICLE AND JUMPTED INTO THE MOVING TRUCK CAB. HE APPLIED THE FOOT PEDAL AND PROPERLY SET THE PARKING BRAKES. DUE TO THE RELEASE OF PRODUCT, THE DISTRICT INITIATED AN EMERGENCY EVACUATION AND CONTACTED LOCAL AUTHORITIES FOR AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE. THE GAS CLOUD DISSIPATED AND THE SITUATION WAS UNDER CONTROL. LOCAL AND STATE AUTHORITIES INSPECTED THE TRANSPORT AND DISCOVERED A FAULTY AIR VALVE. THE UNIT WAS PLACED OUT OF SERVICE AND REPAIRED. THE BULK STORAGE WAS REPAIRED AND RETURNED TO SERVICE.
